  <static seed="73" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/AddThreeFractions40.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{2}{9}}} + {{\frac{5}{6}}} + {{\frac{9}{10}}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1{\textstyle\frac{43}{45}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add fractions with different denominators, we need to find the common denominator first. One way is to list the multiples of the largest denominator, until all <m>3</m> denominators divide into the multiple.</p>
<p>The largest denominator is <m>10</m>. We list its first few multiples:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90 }</m></p>
<p>Note that all denominators, <m>9, 6 \text{ and } 10</m> each divide into <m>90</m>.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{2}{9} + \frac{5}{6} + \frac{9}{10}
      \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 10}{9 \cdot 10} + \frac{5 \cdot 15}{6 \cdot 15} + \frac{9 \cdot 9}{10 \cdot 9} \\
      \amp = \frac{20}{90} + \frac{75}{90} + \frac{81}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{20+75+81}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{176}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{88}{45} \\
        \amp = {1{\textstyle\frac{43}{45}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Don<rsq/>t forget to reduce the fraction <m>\frac{176}{90}</m> by dividing <m>2</m> into both the numerator and the denominator.</p>
</solution>
